'''Burkut''' ('''Bürküt''' or '''Merküt''') is the eagle god in [[Turkic mythology]].

The eagle god Burkut symbolizes the sun and power. The eagle is considered to be the icons of the [[Khagan|khagans]] and [[Khan (title)|khans]] or the symbols of the guardian spirit and justice. In [[Sakha language|Sakha (Yakut)]] culture, the eagle is portrayed on top of the Ulukayın (Tree of Earth). It is either as the symbol of [[Tengri|Tengri (sky god)]]. In the ceremony of sacrifice, a kam ([[Shamanism|shaman]]) chants verses of prayer and summons all the spirits he knowns.<ref>Türklerde İslamiyet Öncesi İnanç Sistemleri - Öğretiler ve Dinler, Erman Artun [http://turkoloji.cu.edu.tr/HALKBILIM/erman_artun_inanc_sistemleri.pdf]</ref> The eagle is referred to as the "bird with copper talons, its right wing covers the sun, the left covers the moon" and son of [[Kayra]].

==In Anatolia==
Among a kind of Turkish folk dances (Turkish: ''[[Yalli|Halay]]'', [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]]: ''Yallı'') are the [[Anatolia]]n "Kartal Halayı" (eagles dance), "Karakuş" (the black bird) and "Karakustana" figures with bravery as the main theme are the figures known as the eagle position.

