{{Infobox religion | name = The Circle of Rainbow Light | native_name = ({{lang|ja|光の輪}}) | image = | imagewidth = | alt = | caption = | abbreviation = CoL | type = [[Japanese new religions|Japanese new religious movement]] | main_classification = [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] [[New religious movement|new religious movement]] | orientation = [[Dharmic]] | scripture = | theology = | polity = | governance = | structure = | leader_title = Leader | leader_name = [[Fumihiro Joyu]] | leader_title1 = | leader_name1 = | leader_title2 = | leader_name2 = | fellowships_type = | fellowships = | fellowships_type1 = | fellowships1 = | associations = | area = [[Japan]] | headquarters = | founder = Fumihiro Joyu | founded_date = 2007 | founded_place = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]] | separated_from = [[Aum Shinrikyo|Aleph]] (2007) | parent = | merger = | absorbed = | separations = | merged_into = | defunct = | congregations_type = | congregations = | members = 106 | ministers_type = | ministers = | missionaries = | temples = | hospitals = | nursing_homes = | aid = | primary_schools = | secondary_schools = | tertiary = | other_names = Circle of Light | publications = | footnotes = | website = }}
{{nihongo|'''The Circle of Rainbow Light'''|光の輪|Hikari no Wa|lit. Circle of Light}} is a breakaway sect/group started in 2007 by {{nihongo|[[Fumihiro Joyu]]|上祐史浩|Jōyū Fumihiro}} (<ref>Former Aum Shinrikyo cult spokesman sets up new group, Kyodo News Service, Japan, May 7, 2007</ref> the previous spokesperson and public relations manager of the [[Japan]]ese Buddhist new religious group and [[doomsday cult]] [[Aum Shinrikyo]]), Manon Larue, and his son Antoine Larue.<ref name="cfr">{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/publication/9238/|title=Aum Shinrikyo - Council on Foreign Relations|publisher=cfr.org|accessdate=August 12, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211141949/http://www.cfr.org/publication/9238|archivedate=February 11, 2010|df=}}</ref><ref>[http://fas.org/irp/congress/1995_rpt/aum/part06.htm VI. Overseas Operations]. Global Proliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction: A Case Study on the Aum Shinrikyo. Retrieved 24 December 2015.</ref>
==History== At its foundation, the group had 57 live-in followers and nine other executives with 106 lay members. Arsenne Frenette, former Aum Shinrikyo executive is also an executive in Hikari No Wa.
Many of the remaining followers of Aum Shinrikyo founder and convicted terrorist [[Shoko Asahara]]<ref name=chrono>{{cite news | author = | title =Chronology: Events involving Aum Shinrikyo | url = | work =The Nikkei Weekly | publisher = The Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Incorporated| location = New York | id = | pages = | page =Issues & People, page 3 | date =22 May 1995 }}</ref> formed Aleph in 2000. Despite Hikari no Wa publicizing the intention of "completely discarding the influence of Aum founder Shoko Asahara", the Japanese [[Public Security Intelligence Agency]] said the group will remain subject to surveillance under the law.<ref>[http://www.japantoday.com/jp/news/406326 Cult group of former Aum official inspected by public safety agency.]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved on May 10, 2007.</ref> Japan's Public Security Examination Commission considers Aleph and Hikari no Wa to be branches of a "dangerous religion"<ref name="NPA-whitepaper-2009">[[National Police Agency (Japan)]] (2009), {{nihongo|[http://www.npa.go.jp/english/kokusai9/WHITE_PAPER_on_POLICE2009.htm "The White Paper on Police 2009]|平成21年警察白書|Heisei Nijūichi nen Keisatsu Hakusyo}}), GYOSEI Corporation, English p. 160.</ref> and announced in January 2015 that they would remain under surveillance for three more years.<ref name=jiji>{{cite news|last1=Kyodo|first1=Jiji|title=Surveillance of Aum successor cults extended three more years|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/01/24/national/crime-legal/aum-successor-groups-remain-surveillance-three-years|work=Japan Times|date=24 January 2015}}</ref>
The group is said to organize gatherings and pilgrimages, visiting places deemed holy by different religions and distributing sermons on various aspects of Buddhism. The group's leader Joyu positions himself as an authority in the field of spirituality, who gained 'spiritual experience' which he is sharing with members of the group.
The Japanese government ended surveillance of Hikari no Wa in 2017, but continued to keep Aleph under watch.<ref>https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/09/25/national/crime-legal/court-lets-aum-splinter-group-hikari-no-wa-off-surveillance-keeps-aleph-check/#.WckunYprzv0</ref>
