This is a list of people noted for having converted to two or more religions or religious movements. Their original religion is mentioned first when applicable. In certain cases the individual considered themselves to be of more than one religion at a time.
*[[Skanderbeg]] - [[Albanians|Albanian]] monarch and military leader, National Hero of Albania, was born as Serbian Orthodox, converted to Islam in his early years, but reverted to Christianity later in life, dying as a Catholic.<ref name = "Skanderbeg">Rendina, Claudio (2000). La grande enciclopedia di Roma. Rome: Newton Compton, 1136. {{ISBN|88-8289-316-2}}.</ref> *[[Nicolas Antoine]] - Started in [[Catholicism]]; conversions Protestantism and Judaism. (not officially admitted to the last one)<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=1608&letter=A Jewish Encyclopedia]</ref> *[[Augustine of Hippo]] - Mixed Catholic/Pagan background with Catholic upbringing; conversions to [[Manichaeism]], [[Neoplatonism]], and finally baptized Catholic.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/02084a.htm Catholic Encyclopedia]</ref> *[[Eldridge Cleaver]] - Conversions/Associations to Nation of Islam then Evangelical Christianity then Mormonism.<ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F50B10F93B5A0C718CDDAC0894D0494D81 New York Times obituary]</ref><ref>[http://www.africanaonline.com/black_panther_e_cleaver.htm Africana Online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100428022717/http://www.africanaonline.com/black_panther_e_cleaver.htm |date=2010-04-28 }}</ref> *[[Rod Dreher]] - Started in [[Methodism]]; conversions to Catholicism<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/05/02/AR2006050201873_pf.html Washington Post]</ref> then Eastern Orthodoxy.<ref>[http://www.myocn.net/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=131&Itemid=153 Orthodox Christian Network]</ref> *[[Daveed Gartenstein-Ross]] - Jewish parents; conversions to Islam then Christianity.<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/11/27/news/memoir.php International Herald Tribune]</ref> *[[Newt Gingrich]] - Lutheran to Baptist to Catholic *[[Tom Hanks]] - Raised primarily in Catholicism then Mormonism; conversions to "born again" Christianity<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/reports/bestof98/the_best_of_1998.cinema2c.html Time Magazine]</ref> and eventually Greek Orthodoxy.<ref>[http://www.ldsfilm.com/actors/TomHanks.html ldsfilm.com]</ref> *[[Martin Harris (Latter Day Saints)|Martin Harris]] - Undetermined Protestantism; Conversions to the Quakers, Universalists, Baptists, Presbyterians,<ref>[[Ronald W. Walker]], "Martin Harris: Mormonism's Early Convert," ''[[Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought]]'' 19 (Winter 1986):30-33.</ref> and several denominations of [[Mormonism]],<ref>[http://direct.bl.uk/bld/PlaceOrder.do?UIN=184753258&ETOC=RN&from=searchengine British Library on his mission for the Strangites]</ref> Also may have been Methodist for a time. Known among Mormons as one of the [[Three Witnesses]]. *[[Lex Hixon]] - Not raised religious; Conversions to [[Vedanta]], [[Sufism]]. Eastern Orthodox Christianity, and possibly [[Zen]]. *[[Muhammad Khodabandeh (Oljeitu)]] - Nestorian Christian upbringing; Buddhism, [[Sunni Islam]], and [[Shia Islam]] *[[David Kirk (activist)|David Kirk]] - Originally Baptist; became a deacon in the [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church]] and later converted to the [[Orthodox Church in America]].<ref>[http://www.oca.org/Mem.asp?ID=73&SID=18 OCA obituary]</ref> *[[Debi Mazar]] - Originally Catholic; Actress who reportedly converted to Buddhism, Judaism, and briefly the Jehovah's Witnesses.<ref>[http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/tv/11883/index1.html NY Metro]</ref> *[[Ibrahim Njoya]] - [[Bamum people]] religion; back and forth [[conversions from Islam]] to Christianity.<ref>[http://www.africa.ufl.edu/asq/v7/v7i1a4.htm African Studies Quarterly] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206232021/http://www.africa.ufl.edu/asq/v7/v7i1a4.htm |date=2012-02-06 }}</ref> Also created his own religion.<ref>[http://dubois.fas.harvard.edu/research_projects/bamun_art_worlds.html W. E. B. Du Bois Institute for African and African American Research at Harvard] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014005216/http://dubois.fas.harvard.edu/research_projects/bamun_art_worlds.html |date=2008-10-14 }}</ref> * [[Sinéad O'Connor]] (Shuhada' Davitt) – [[Irish people|Irish]] singer-songwriter; a former [[Excommunication|excommunicated]] Roman Catholic before becoming as [[Nondenominational Christianity|Nondenominational Trinitarian Christian]] for several years and later [Sunni] Islam due of theological reasons<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iambirmingham.co.uk/2018/10/25/singer-sinead-oconnor-converts-islam-changes-name/|title=Singer Sinead O'Connor converts to Islam and changes her name {{!}} I Am Birmingham|date=2018-10-25|work=I Am Birmingham|access-date=2018-10-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishpost.com/entertainment/sinead-oconnor-renounces-catholicism-converts-islam-161261|title=Sinead O'Connor renounces Catholicism and converts to Islam|last=Lonergan|first=Aidan|work=The Irish Post|access-date=2018-10-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> *[[J. D. Salinger]] - Started in [[Judaism]]; converted or experimented with Zen Buddhism, Advaita Vedanta, Dianetics, and Christian Science.<ref>[http://www.adherents.com/people/ps/JD_Salinger.html Adherents.com]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/10/08/reviews/001008.08rosenbt.html Dream Catcher: A Memoir by Margaret Salinger]</ref> *[[Ignaz Trebitsch-Lincoln]] - Born an Orthodox Jew, he converted to Lutheranism to escape Austro-Hungarian authorities, and then converted to both [[Presbyterianism]] and [[Anglicanism]] and then finally converted to [[Buddhism]] towards the end of his life. *[[Theophan Prokopovich]] - Born and raised an Orthodox Christianity, he converted to Eastern Catholicism in order to achieve better educational benefits, but reverted to Orthodox Christianity later in life. ==References== {{Reflist|2}}
