'''Peter Saxon''' is a ''[[nom de plume]]'' used by various [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]] authors from the 1950s to the 1970s.
==History== The pseudonym "Peter Saxon" was originally used by Irish [[wiktionary|pulp fiction]] writer and journalist W. Howard Baker at [[Amalgamated Press]], mostly for novels in the [[Sexton Blake]] series.<ref name="dictionary">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qQoeCwAAQBAJ|title=A Dictionary of Literary Pseudonyms in the English Language|first=T.J.|last=Carty|publisher=Routledge|date=2015|isbn=1135955786|}}</ref><ref name="kalat">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LDaSCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA215|title=The Strange Case of Dr. Mabuse: A Study of the Twelve Films and Five Novels|first=David|last=Kalat|publisher=McFarland|date=2012|isbn=1476601070|}}</ref> One of these Sexton Blake novels, ''Crime Is My Business'', was made into the 1958 film, ''[[Murder at Site 3]]'', by [[Hammer Film Productions]].<ref name="bfi"'>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6b0e883c|title=Murder at Site Three (1959)|website=bfi.org.uk|}}</ref> In 1965, Baker moved to a different publisher, Mayflower Books, and continued writing Sexton Blake novels as "Peter Saxon", but Mayflower also began to use this pen-name as a house pseudonym for works by other authors.<ref name="kalat"/> ''The Disorientated Man'' was a Peter Saxon [[conspiracy thriller]] mainly written by Stephen Frances and edited by Baker; it was adapted as the 1970 film, ''[[Scream and Scream Again]]'', starring [[Vincent Price]], [[Christopher Lee]], [[Alfred Marks]], [[Michael Gothard]], and [[Peter Cushing]].<ref name="kalat"/> The [[occult detective fiction]] series ''The Guardians'' was another Peter Saxon title, with writers including Baker, Rex Dolphin, Wilfred McNeilly,<ref name="hendrix">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Gk7KDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA14#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Paperbacks from Hell: The Twisted History of '70s and '80s Horror Fiction|first=Grady|last=Hendrix|publisher=Quirk Books|date=2017|isbn=1594749825|}}</ref> and Thomas Martin.<ref name="dictionary"/>
